1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,500
[SPEAKER_00] I'm going to talk a little bit about an overview of the cover bond market today and how it got there.

2
00:00:09,500 --> 00:00:17,500
[SPEAKER_00] I'll talk a little bit about the definition of actually what a covered bond is, something that Boris just spoke about very briefly earlier.

3
00:00:17,500 --> 00:00:25,000
[SPEAKER_00] And I think more importantly in a new country that's coming to the market for the first time, look at some of the possible objections to covered bonds.

4
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] Some of the things that can go wrong, some of the things that people might not like.

5
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:34,000
[SPEAKER_00] And then finally I'll speak about some of the hot topics in the cover bond market that we're talking about today

6
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] that are going to come up in some of the other speeches that we hear today.

7
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:44,000
[SPEAKER_00] After that I'm then going to hand over to the EBRD to Jacek and Andrea to talk a little bit about

8
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] what the EBRD does in the cover bond market in more detail than Pierre went to.

9
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] So first of all let's just talk about the size of the cover bond market.

10
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:59,000
[SPEAKER_00] I think the first thing is it's a very large market but it could be much larger.

11
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:04,000
[SPEAKER_00] We have roughly two and a half trillion euros of covered bonds outstanding.

12
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now not all of them are backed by residential mortgages.

13
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] Not all of them are in Europe.

14
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] Roughly speaking we have about two trillion of mortgages funded through the cover bond market in Europe at the moment.

15
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] If you compare that to the total market stock of about seven trillion,

16
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] roughly 30% of all houses in Europe are funded through the covered bond market.

17
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] When you think of deposits, central bank money, LTRO, all of the other sources of banking,

18
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:41,000
[SPEAKER_00] 30% is really quite a high number.

19
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:47,000
[SPEAKER_00] One comparison that I like to make is it's very similar to the share that Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac have in America

20
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] of the American residential mortgage market.

21
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:57,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now that 30% though, that covers literally, there's a very, very wide range, literally zero to a hundred.

22
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:02,000
[SPEAKER_00] In Denmark, every single mortgage is funded through a covered bond.

23
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:07,000
[SPEAKER_00] And in many countries, including obviously here, we don't have any covered bonds outstanding at all.

24
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:12,000
[SPEAKER_00] A lot of people spend a lot of time talking about Germany in this market for very good reasons.

25
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] But actually the German percentage of German houses that are funded through the covered bond market is roughly the average.

26
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's a little bit below 30%.

27
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] There are other reasons why Germany is so important when we talk about covered bonds.

28
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] And I'll come on to some of those.

29
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] Just to apply those numbers to Croatia, there are about seven billion residential mortgages outstanding in Croatia at the moment.

30
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:47,000
[SPEAKER_00] So simple maths, if we had the same ratio, we'd have about two, 2.2 billion of covered bonds outstanding.

31
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:49,000
[SPEAKER_00] That's a really dumb way to calculate it.

32
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's a very simplistic way to calculate it.

33
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:58,000
[SPEAKER_00] More importantly, that seven billion euros represents, I've noted it down, about 15% of GDP.

34
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] On a European average, that's quite low.

35
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] The average across the whole of Europe is about 45 to 50% of GDP, the size of the residential mortgage market.

36
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] So you're about a third of the average relative to GDP.

37
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:19,000
[SPEAKER_00] And of course GDP is below the European Union average.

38
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:29,000
[SPEAKER_00] And so if you translate it into per capita terms, the average Croatian has about 2,000 euros of mortgage debt.

39
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] The average European has about 16,000.

40
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:42,000
[SPEAKER_00] And so the potential growth of the market, doing the maths, is about an eight times potential increase, which works out at about 50 billion of new funding.

41
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, of course, we're not going to converge tomorrow with the same GDP, with the same mortgage to GDP ratio.

42
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:55,000
[SPEAKER_00] But if you were, that would be about a 50 billion euro funding gap.

43
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:00,000
[SPEAKER_00] I said that this could be a much, much larger market.

44
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:04,000
[SPEAKER_00] I put this graph, not because the numbers are particularly relevant.

45
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:05,000
[SPEAKER_00] There's one interesting thing.

46
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] The cover bond market overall grew, grew, grew until about 2012.

47
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:11,000
[SPEAKER_00] It grew through the financial crisis.

48
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:14,000
[SPEAKER_00] It grew through all of the bad years up until then.

49
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:16,000
[SPEAKER_00] And then it shrunk.

50
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:17,000
[UNKNOWN] Slightly.

51
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:19,000
[SPEAKER_00] More or less plateaued.

52
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] It stopped growing despite the cost savings, despite new countries coming online, starting to issue cover bonds for the fullest time, like Canada, like Singapore, like Australia.

53
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:34,000
[SPEAKER_00] Why is that?

54
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:41,000
[SPEAKER_00] Well, I think that there are a few contributing factors, one of which obviously is the huge amounts of liquidity in the system.

55
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:45,000
[SPEAKER_00] Boris previously spoke about the structural liquidity surplus here.

56
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's a structural liquidity surplus in a lot of countries with the amount of money that comes from central banks into the market.

57
00:04:51,000 --> 00:05:03,000
[SPEAKER_00] When we'll see a normalization of that and a reduction of an amortization of the TL, TROs, the ECB, then presumably there'll be more of an onus on market funding.

58
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] And presumably the cover bond market can approximate to its normal run rate.

59
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:13,000
[SPEAKER_00] The other point is actually we've seen extremely low mortgage growth in most of Europe.

60
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:17,000
[SPEAKER_00] About 1% year on year for the last five years.

61
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:25,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now that's slightly below average growth rates, significantly below average or total mortgage size.

62
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] In Germany, the UK, Sweden, several large economies, the mortgage market is growing very significantly, so the house prices are growing very significantly.

63
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] But mortgage markets aren't growing as quickly.

64
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:47,000
[SPEAKER_00] If there was a catch up in terms of the amount of mortgages funded, we'd see a very significant increase in the number of covered bonds outstanding.

65
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] So, yeah, I think that's all I'd like to say about the market as it stands at the moment.

66
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:59,000
[SPEAKER_00] And, of course, you can quote numbers about the total new funding need.

67
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:03,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's suffice to say that there's a lot of potential use of this product in the medium term.

68
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] I love history, but I don't want to bore you too much with it.

69
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:13,000
[SPEAKER_00] I only want to touch on some things which I think are relevant for the cover bond market.

70
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:23,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, the first date up here, 1769, I have no idea whether it's true, but all of my German friends assure me that Fanbrief have existed since 1769.

71
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] I think that has two important repercussions.

72
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] The first one is that next year is going to be 250 years, so there's going to be some great parties.

73
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] More importantly, it's something which I think is very deep in the German psyche.

74
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:42,000
[SPEAKER_00] Whether it's true or not, it's a myth or it's reality.

75
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] The fact that people believe that this market has been around for 250 years really makes people very conservative about it, very protective of it.

76
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:59,000
[SPEAKER_00] Very wanting sometimes to be parochial about it, to close the doors to newcomers, sometimes wanting to export it, but say, don't mess around with these concepts.

77
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:03,000
[SPEAKER_00] Do it like we do it. Don't try to be different about it.

78
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:14,000
[SPEAKER_00] I think whenever you speak to the protectors of the Fanbrief, the German covered bond market, they're very conscious of this history and you've got to be very aware of it.

79
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:26,000
[SPEAKER_00] Another important point, a defining thing for the cover bond market was the mid-90s when Germany had huge funding needs.

80
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] We're so used to Germany being an exporter of capital for the last 15 years.

81
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:35,000
[SPEAKER_00] We forget in the 90s, it was a massive importer of capital to fund reunification.

82
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] One of the most effective tools that Germany had to bring foreign money into Deutsche Marks was the Fanbrief market.

83
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] It grew to slightly over a trillion outstanding around 2000, 2002, 2003.

84
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:56,000
[SPEAKER_00] A lot of this was on the idea of what we call the jumbo covered bond.

85
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:04,000
[SPEAKER_00] A jumbo covered bond has various definitions, but basically means it's a very big covered bond that we promise is going to be liquid in secondary trading.

86
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] That was really important to position it as a rival to government bonds in many ways.

87
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] It was a great, in 1995 when they came up with the idea of market making commitments.

88
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] I'll always be able to sell the bond with this bid-ask spread.

89
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] It sounds a bit crazy really nowadays with what we've seen since.

90
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:25,000
[SPEAKER_00] But it's an incredibly powerful selling tool.

91
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] To people in the past would have just bought German government bonds.

92
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:35,000
[SPEAKER_00] That was a real fillip to the development of the market in other countries.

93
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] The other one is 2003 when we first saw the first contract law covered bonds.

94
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:49,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, up until 2003, every single covered bond had been a law was passed by parliament and then we'd go ahead with that.

95
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:55,000
[SPEAKER_00] In the UK, because of English law, which is quite flexible in many ways,

96
00:08:55,000 --> 00:09:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] and because of securitization technology, which achieves all the things that in other countries you need a law to do,

97
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:04,000
[SPEAKER_00] we were able, I actually worked on structuring this deal,

98
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] we were able to create something that looked, smelt, felt like a covered bond, purely using contract law.

99
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, that's not possible in most countries, but what it did is it really gave a good kick to those countries that thought we need a covered bond law.

100
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] And lots of banks were clamoring in a lot of countries, in Spain, in Portugal, in Finland, in Holland, in Italy,

101
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] were all saying we need something like the family system.

102
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:33,000
[SPEAKER_00] And hey, the Brits have just done it under contract law.

103
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] And in all of those countries, we had a very busy few years working with governments in all of those countries,

104
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:45,000
[SPEAKER_00] bringing online covered bond laws to try to replicate this in many ways.

105
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:52,000
[SPEAKER_00] And this is where we went from three or four large countries to 20 countries issuing covered bonds.

106
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:57,000
[SPEAKER_00] And then the final thing, and it's something that we're going to talk about a little bit,

107
00:09:57,000 --> 00:10:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] which is this year, it's a very hot topic at the moment, is the directive.

108
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:07,000
[SPEAKER_00] For the first time ever, there's a covered bond directive, and I think many speakers will talk about that today.

109
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] Florian and myself will have a chat about it later.

110
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] Why does history matter? Well, as I say, there's some significant points here.

111
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] The conservatism I've already mentioned, how ingrained it is in the financial system is very important to how you structure a covered bond.

112
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:29,000
[SPEAKER_00] Does the regulator know, understand, have a department full of people who can stress test covered bonds,

113
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] or are they learning from scratch?

114
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:33,000
[SPEAKER_00] How does it interact with other financing tools?

115
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] Is it a complement to securitization, or is it a rival?

116
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] And I think the other thing, an important one, is success creates challenges.

117
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:47,000
[SPEAKER_00] This is quite rightly perceived as an incredibly successful financing tool,

118
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] which has worked really well for many years in many countries.

119
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:55,000
[SPEAKER_00] Therefore, why don't we use it in other things, more risky things?

120
00:10:55,000 --> 00:10:58,000
[SPEAKER_00] Other asset classes are going to be included as part of the directive.

121
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:03,000
[SPEAKER_00] Using covered bond technology to fund loans to small and medium-sized enterprises,

122
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:07,000
[SPEAKER_00] maybe to fund green loans, maybe to fund infrastructure projects.

123
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] That's a challenge to that conservative mindset.

124
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] But it's one I think we need to take up because of the effectiveness of this tool.

125
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:17,000
[SPEAKER_00] And also, new countries.

126
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] Possibly this year, possibly next year, we're going to see the first Brazilian covered bond.

127
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:29,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, that's a really radical step for such a conservative market that is so used to triple-A,

128
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] or at worst double-A rated bonds most of the time.

129
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] To start going outside Europe into emerging markets like Brazil,

130
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] it's a bit of a shock to a very established system.

131
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] And I've said all this without actually saying what a covered bond is,

132
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:46,000
[SPEAKER_00] a fairly fundamental thing which I guess I ought to mention.

133
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:53,000
[SPEAKER_00] Boris earlier briefly mentioned this idea that it's like a securitization with recourse.

134
00:11:53,000 --> 00:11:56,000
[SPEAKER_00] There's a little bit more to that, but that's a good starting point.

135
00:11:56,000 --> 00:11:58,000
[SPEAKER_00] It is a dual recourse instrument.

136
00:11:58,000 --> 00:12:04,000
[SPEAKER_00] In all of the definition, you can just do it with how it differs from securitization.

137
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:07,000
[SPEAKER_00] So, I think the first point is it has to be issued by a bank.

138
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:12,000
[SPEAKER_00] Securitizations are usually issued by banks, but can be issued by leasing companies,

139
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:17,000
[SPEAKER_00] by finance companies, by corporates even, if they have assets that you think you can turn into a bond.

140
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] Here, it must be issued by a bank for one very important reason,

141
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:26,000
[SPEAKER_00] that you have this supervisory oversight, actually the third box here.

142
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] You have a dedicated law, you have a dedicated supervisory regime.

143
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:36,000
[SPEAKER_00] That regime must exist to protect the interests of covered bond holders.

144
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:41,000
[SPEAKER_00] It doesn't guarantee the covered bonds, but it guarantees that somebody in the public sector has gone,

145
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:46,000
[SPEAKER_00] has looked at it, has stress tested the pool, has made sure that it complies with the law,

146
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] has made sure that it's as safe as it can be within the context of the covered bond law

147
00:12:51,000 --> 00:12:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] and what the regulations allow.

148
00:12:54,000 --> 00:12:59,000
[SPEAKER_00] I think that's an important point that is often forgotten in covered bonds.

149
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:04,000
[SPEAKER_00] The other point is, yes, it's backed by a pool of assets, just like securitizations,

150
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] but a very important difference is in a securitization, you have a static pool of assets,

151
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:11,000
[SPEAKER_00] what I call a fire and forget pool.

152
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:13,000
[SPEAKER_00] Here's my assets, I put them in this pool,

153
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:17,000
[SPEAKER_00] and if they don't work, that's your problem, bond holder, not my problem.

154
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:24,000
[SPEAKER_00] By nature of this being full recourse, it's a full recourse to the bank, there's no point in that.

155
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] There's no risk transfer going on to the bond holders, so I have to keep the pool current.

156
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:36,000
[SPEAKER_00] If something goes wrong in the pool, if this mortgage defaults, this mortgage goes into arrears,

157
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] typically I replace it.

158
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] And one of the very interesting case studies of this market, and it's an illustration of how well it's worked,

159
00:13:43,000 --> 00:13:46,000
[SPEAKER_00] is when you look at covered bonds in countries like Greece or Ireland,

160
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] which have had obviously massive problems with their residential mortgage markets,

161
00:13:51,000 --> 00:13:55,000
[SPEAKER_00] in those countries the cover pools looked absolutely fantastic through the crisis

162
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:59,000
[SPEAKER_00] because of this constant replenishment of the bad with the good.

163
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:04,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's a very important thing which has kept cover bond ratings incredibly stable

164
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] and has prevented any defaults through the crisis.

165
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:12,000
[SPEAKER_00] So when you have all of those things, what's the outcome?

166
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:14,000
[SPEAKER_00] It is a covered bond.

167
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:19,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, I know Jacek always loves this one, securitisations are in many ways a technique

168
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] that can be applied to all kinds of different things in many different ways.

169
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:24,000
[SPEAKER_00] Cover bonds are a brand.

170
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] What we have here is a distinct thing.

171
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] A legally protected title.

172
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:34,000
[SPEAKER_00] A guarantee of quality, quite frankly.

173
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] And when you get into the EU directives, it's a lower risk rating.

174
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] It has higher eligibility for liquidity pools.

175
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:47,000
[SPEAKER_00] It has all kinds of very nice features as a consequence of this brand and this protection.

176
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] So that is what we're trying to do here.

177
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:53,000
[SPEAKER_00] I'm not going to spend very long on this slide.

178
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:57,000
[SPEAKER_00] Because it's frankly not very important.

179
00:14:57,000 --> 00:15:02,000
[SPEAKER_00] There are many different ways across Europe to structure covered bonds.

180
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:07,000
[SPEAKER_00] You can put them into a special bank that only does cover bond-y things and is owned by a real bank.

181
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:11,000
[SPEAKER_00] You can segregate a pool of assets on the balance sheet of a bank.

182
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] Or you can shift a pool of assets into a separate SPV that writes a guarantee of the bond.

183
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, that looks like fairly fundamental differences.

184
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:25,000
[SPEAKER_00] But in reality, it only matters to cover bond nerds like me and lawyers and rating agencies.

185
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] Investors generally are indifferent.

186
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] If they get a AAA rating, I don't care about the boxes and arrows too much.

187
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] There's no real difference in the amount of rating uplift that you can achieve.

188
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] You can achieve AAA.

189
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] There are AAA examples in all three of these models.

190
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:45,000
[SPEAKER_00] It doesn't really influence the spread of the bonds very much.

191
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:49,000
[SPEAKER_00] It matters to minute legal details.

192
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:52,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, we use these different structures in different countries.

193
00:15:52,000 --> 00:15:57,000
[SPEAKER_00] Every country has a different set of starting points, set of conditions that we need to work with.

194
00:15:57,000 --> 00:15:59,000
[SPEAKER_00] We don't just randomly pick one of these.

195
00:15:59,000 --> 00:16:02,000
[SPEAKER_00] It isn't an arbitrary decision.

196
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] There are important things like, are there negative pledge clauses in existing documentation?

197
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:12,000
[SPEAKER_00] Is it legally possible to create ring fencing on balance sheet?

198
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:14,000
[SPEAKER_00] Is it commercially viable to set up special banks?

199
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:16,000
[SPEAKER_00] Those kind of starting points.

200
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] But when we've addressed those, you don't really need to worry about it as an issuer or as an investor too much.

201
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:29,000
[SPEAKER_00] I'm happy to discuss it, but I want to play down the importance of that, to be honest.

202
00:16:29,000 --> 00:16:35,000
[SPEAKER_00] More importantly, let's just talk about some of the things that I've heard that have said,

203
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] we don't want covered bonds because.

204
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:42,000
[SPEAKER_00] One of the most common ones is, if you've ever seen the film The Big Short,

205
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:48,000
[SPEAKER_00] it's about the worst excesses of the US subprime and taking those mortgages and turning them into bonds.

206
00:16:48,000 --> 00:16:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] Very irresponsible lending, origination purely to distribute mortgages.

207
00:16:54,000 --> 00:16:55,000
[SPEAKER_00] I'm not going to hold the risk.

208
00:16:55,000 --> 00:16:59,000
[SPEAKER_00] I'm going to pass it on to bondholders all the way through the capital spectrum.

209
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:02,000
[SPEAKER_00] So I'm not going to produce any old rubbish.

210
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:05,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's a very valid concern about the securitization market.

211
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:11,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's one that the securitization directive has addressed very well under EU law.

212
00:17:11,000 --> 00:17:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's not valid in covered bonds because of this risk retention, because of this dual recourse.

213
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:23,000
[SPEAKER_00] Because of that and also because of the very high level of transparency you have.

214
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] The covered bond market has a reasonable level of transparency mandated by law by the European Union directive.

215
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:34,000
[SPEAKER_00] But in practice in the market, it has much more.

216
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] We have something called the covered bond label, which most issuers sign up to.

217
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:44,000
[SPEAKER_00] And they have incredibly detailed templates of what's in the pool in a very user friendly format.

218
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:47,000
[SPEAKER_00] That stops these kind of the bad stuff getting in there.

219
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] Or if it gets in there, investors will know about it.

220
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:52,000
[SPEAKER_00] And then the supervisory process.

221
00:17:52,000 --> 00:18:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] As I mentioned, the individual day-to-day supervision of the pool does a lot to protect this kind of irresponsible lending.

222
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:02,000
[SPEAKER_00] Does it encourage more lending?

223
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:05,000
[SPEAKER_00] There's possibly more validity to this.

224
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:17,000
[SPEAKER_00] If you look at the growth of the Spanish mortgage market from 2004 to 2007, 2008, a very large amount of that was funded by covered bonds.

225
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, I'm going to defend covered bonds and say it wasn't covered bonds fault.

226
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] The correct way to rein in excessive mortgage growth is pillar two capital, general supervisory tools, better pricing of the risk.

227
00:18:32,000 --> 00:18:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] Not by stopping people from accessing a very effective term funding tool for it.

228
00:18:38,000 --> 00:18:45,000
[SPEAKER_00] And I think the other important thing, and sorry, I don't want to slag off securitization because securitization is very important.

229
00:18:45,000 --> 00:18:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] Securitization has been used as a way to circumvent some of those risk management tools.

230
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:55,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's a way of reducing the regulatory capital usage of residential mortgages.

231
00:18:55,000 --> 00:18:57,000
[SPEAKER_00] We don't do that in covered bonds.

232
00:18:57,000 --> 00:19:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] Then on the more sort of important stuff, the consumer rights.

233
00:19:01,000 --> 00:19:12,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's very important when you're structuring a covered bond that the individual borrower is in no way prejudiced from an issuer's decision to put them into the program.

234
00:19:12,000 --> 00:19:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] On a practical level, the person managing the program, making a decision about whether I'm going to give forbearance when they're in arrears, offering them new products.

235
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] It doesn't know whether the mortgage is in the pool or not in the pool.

236
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] They're just sitting there in the bank operating as normal.

237
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] The fact that the mortgage is in the pool or not is something which happens behind the scenes in the IT platform with a little flag saying it's in the pool, it isn't in the pool.

238
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:42,000
[SPEAKER_00] The general way that the customer is treated should be identical.

239
00:19:42,000 --> 00:20:00,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's very important that you address all of these things like the banking secrecy, privity of contract, rights to reasonable forbearance when you're structuring the rules and the regulations to make sure that from an equitable point of view there's no bad consequences from being included in the pool.

240
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:05,000
[SPEAKER_00] It costs the government revenue.

241
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:12,000
[SPEAKER_00] So quite often you have to transfer mortgages and you get notice saying, hang on a second, you used to pay me when you transfer mortgages.

242
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] And you're suddenly transferring 10,000 and not having any revenue coming in.

243
00:20:18,000 --> 00:20:21,000
[SPEAKER_00] Same objection to the land registry.

244
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:25,000
[SPEAKER_00] In all cases when we're trying to structure a covered bond, we're not trying to avoid any of these things.

245
00:20:25,000 --> 00:20:26,000
[SPEAKER_00] We're not trying to incur any.

246
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] We're trying to be completely neutral for any kind of costs like this.

247
00:20:30,000 --> 00:20:36,000
[SPEAKER_00] The transfer of 10,000 mortgages into a cover pool wouldn't happen if it wasn't for the covered bond.

248
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] In many ways it's a legal transfer only.

249
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:41,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's not actually any substantial thing.

250
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:44,000
[SPEAKER_00] The mortgages are going to come back when the bond matures.

251
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:47,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's purely a legal way of ring fencing.

252
00:20:47,000 --> 00:20:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] We don't want to incur any costs and we don't want to avoid any costs by doing it.

253
00:20:51,000 --> 00:20:52,000
[SPEAKER_00] We just want a neutral.

254
00:20:52,000 --> 00:20:53,000
[SPEAKER_00] And the same for tax.

255
00:20:53,000 --> 00:20:58,000
[SPEAKER_00] We don't want anything other than the reality that this is a regular bond issued by a bank.

256
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:00,000
[SPEAKER_00] And we don't want to incur any new tax.

257
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:07,000
[SPEAKER_00] One of the objections that I've heard in some countries is covered bonds compete with government bonds.

258
00:21:07,000 --> 00:21:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] Typically they're very well rated.

259
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:11,000
[SPEAKER_00] Typically they're very liquid.

260
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:19,000
[SPEAKER_00] In many countries in Europe, Spain, Italy, Portugal, they actually trade at a tighter spread than the government bond.

261
00:21:19,000 --> 00:21:21,000
[SPEAKER_00] I think it's a valid concern.

262
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's more of a problem if you're issuing in a domestic currency than in the Eurozone.

263
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:36,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's more of a problem for governments with high borrowing requirements and lower credit ratings where this is valid.

264
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:42,000
[SPEAKER_00] But it's an objection which has to be discussed and mentioned as part of the discussion.

265
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:48,000
[SPEAKER_00] Does it increase the connectivity between banks, the riskiness between banks?

266
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] I think it's a challenge.

267
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] I buy your bonds.

268
00:21:51,000 --> 00:21:52,000
[SPEAKER_00] You buy my bonds.

269
00:21:52,000 --> 00:21:53,000
[SPEAKER_00] We have a greater connection.

270
00:21:53,000 --> 00:22:00,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's less of a problem than banks buying each other's capital, obviously.

271
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:02,000
[SPEAKER_00] But it's a valid point.

272
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] I think it applies much more, again, if you have a domestic market, if you don't have such a developed non-bank investor base.

273
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:24,000
[SPEAKER_00] And frankly, I know Boris has left the room, but it depends a lot on the ECB, on the central bank's policy towards taking those bonds as collateral from banks in repo transactions.

274
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:27,000
[SPEAKER_00] And then the final point is, does it subordinate other creditors?

275
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:33,000
[SPEAKER_00] By virtue of drawing a ring fencing around the bank's best assets, do the other creditors of the bank somehow lose out?

276
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:35,000
[SPEAKER_00] Well, yes, frankly, they do a bit.

277
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] What is the materiality of that compared to the materiality of the benefits?

278
00:22:40,000 --> 00:22:46,000
[SPEAKER_00] I think Andrea and Jacek in a minute are going to speak a little bit about some of the benefits of covered bonds.

279
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:48,000
[SPEAKER_00] They're enormous benefits.

280
00:22:48,000 --> 00:23:05,000
[SPEAKER_00] The incremental loss given default by virtue of a ring fenced pool of assets for the covered bond creditors is very, very small relative to the lower probability of default of that bank because they have access to this term funding market.

281
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] These are objections we've heard in many countries.

282
00:23:09,000 --> 00:23:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] Some of them are very valid.

283
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:12,000
[SPEAKER_00] Some of them have to be discussed.

284
00:23:12,000 --> 00:23:19,000
[SPEAKER_00] We always like to flush them out early in the process to make sure that we don't have any hidden objections.

285
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:26,000
[SPEAKER_00] There are countries where the process is just owned by one ministry or what were the national bank.

286
00:23:26,000 --> 00:23:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] And, you know, it's very important.

287
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] And this kind of gathering is great to have this kind of dialogue.

288
00:23:31,000 --> 00:23:35,000
[SPEAKER_00] What could possibly go wrong with the covered bond market?

289
00:23:35,000 --> 00:23:37,000
[SPEAKER_00] Well, actually quite a lot of things.

290
00:23:37,000 --> 00:23:42,000
[SPEAKER_00] There are loads of countries out there where there aren't any covered bonds.

291
00:23:42,000 --> 00:23:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] Okay.

292
00:23:43,000 --> 00:23:47,000
[SPEAKER_00] There are loads where there are some covered bonds, but it really doesn't work.

293
00:23:47,000 --> 00:23:49,000
[SPEAKER_00] Bulgaria is my favorite example.

294
00:23:49,000 --> 00:23:52,000
[SPEAKER_00] They passed a covered bond law something like 20 years ago.

295
00:23:52,000 --> 00:23:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] There's 5 million euros outstanding.

296
00:23:54,000 --> 00:23:56,000
[SPEAKER_00] It basically doesn't work.

297
00:23:56,000 --> 00:24:05,000
[SPEAKER_00] And an awful lot of effort, an awful lot of political capital has been spent putting a law through parliament, putting all the regulations in place.

298
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] And if it doesn't meet the market's needs or it's too expensive or it's too onerous or there's commercial problems, it just doesn't happen.

299
00:24:15,000 --> 00:24:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] And there are several cases around Europe of that.

300
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:24,000
[SPEAKER_00] There are countries where there is lots of issuance, but actually the covered bond law isn't very good.

301
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] And as a consequence of that, and I'm sure Moody's will have something to say on this, if the covered bond law isn't good, you throw more collateral at it.

302
00:24:31,000 --> 00:24:34,000
[SPEAKER_00] You have a higher over collateralization ratio.

303
00:24:34,000 --> 00:24:44,000
[SPEAKER_00] In Spain, they have a 25% over collateralization ratio, which is the statutory, is the highest in Europe by far, because actually the covered bond law isn't very good there.

304
00:24:44,000 --> 00:24:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] They can still get to AAA, but only by virtue of very poor collateral efficiency.

305
00:24:50,000 --> 00:24:53,000
[SPEAKER_00] And another problem is barriers to entry.

306
00:24:53,000 --> 00:25:03,000
[SPEAKER_00] If you pick the wrong model, and if you don't get the costs right up front, lots of people are going to be excluded from the covered bond market, lots of smaller players.

307
00:25:03,000 --> 00:25:11,000
[SPEAKER_00] And in a lot of countries, in Australia, for example, for many years, the objection to covered bonds was, it's just for the big banks.

308
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's just for the players who have easy access to funding.

309
00:25:15,000 --> 00:25:19,000
[SPEAKER_00] And we small banks, we're just going to lose out because we don't have access to this funding tool.

310
00:25:19,000 --> 00:25:25,000
[SPEAKER_00] So it's very important to make sure that it doesn't distort competition by giving this benefit.

311
00:25:26,000 --> 00:25:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] There are many reasons. I don't want to go into too much detail about where people have gone wrong.

312
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:42,000
[SPEAKER_00] I'll just mention the last one, and I love this Jimi Hendrix quote here.

313
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:48,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's very, very easy to copy Germany, frankly.

314
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:55,000
[SPEAKER_00] German cover bond market is the first amongst equals. It's fantastic. It works very well.

315
00:25:55,000 --> 00:25:58,000
[SPEAKER_00] It works very well in Germany.

316
00:25:58,000 --> 00:26:03,000
[SPEAKER_00] In Germany, you have, it's been part of the architecture, as I mentioned earlier, for a very long time.

317
00:26:03,000 --> 00:26:06,000
[SPEAKER_00] Everyone understands it. Everyone knows it.

318
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] You have very long fixed rate mortgages.

319
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:13,000
[SPEAKER_00] You have very clear mortgage lending value rather than market value as the basis of valuations.

320
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] Many things which don't apply in other countries, but that doesn't stop other countries trying to copy them.

321
00:26:20,000 --> 00:26:26,000
[SPEAKER_00] My favourite example of this was in Romania, when we were trying to put in place the secondary regulations.

322
00:26:26,000 --> 00:26:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] There was a comment that, for valuation purposes, we have to use the mortgage lending value

323
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:36,000
[SPEAKER_00] because that's what they use in Germany, and Germany's got the best covered bond law.

324
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] And all the banks are, there's no concept of mortgage lending value in this country.

325
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:42,000
[SPEAKER_00] All we have is market value.

326
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:47,000
[SPEAKER_00] So, if we were going to do this, we'd have to go back into every single mortgage,

327
00:26:47,000 --> 00:26:52,000
[SPEAKER_00] invent a concept of mortgage lending value, and revalue every single mortgage on that basis.

328
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] That's a deal killer for us.

329
00:26:54,000 --> 00:26:56,000
[SPEAKER_00] And eventually we said, well, no, just because Germany does it,

330
00:26:56,000 --> 00:27:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] doesn't mean it's necessarily the right thing to do outside Germany.

331
00:27:01,000 --> 00:27:05,000
[SPEAKER_00] I'm going to very, very briefly talk about this.

332
00:27:05,000 --> 00:27:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] Some of the things that we talk about in covered bond land.

333
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] New asset classes.

334
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:16,000
[SPEAKER_00] I mentioned earlier the idea that this tool works so well, let's use it to do other things outside the tradition.

335
00:27:16,000 --> 00:27:19,000
[SPEAKER_00] Covered bond directive, we're going to be mentioning earlier.

336
00:27:19,000 --> 00:27:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] Green bonds.

337
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] Whenever you go to this kind of event, you have to talk about the opportunities to improve climate measures, all of those kind of things.

338
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:34,000
[SPEAKER_00] There is a sector of green covered bonds.

339
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's not a very large sector, but it's an interesting development.

340
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:49,000
[SPEAKER_00] And as I say, the new countries, which you can basically break down into the, let's say, the anglosphere.

341
00:27:49,000 --> 00:27:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] Those countries with very nice ratings, you have basically an English legal system.

342
00:27:54,000 --> 00:27:58,000
[SPEAKER_00] Singapore, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, who have copied our models.

343
00:27:58,000 --> 00:28:05,000
[SPEAKER_00] Those countries that are outside Europe and not investment grade, we're going to see the first Malaysian covered bond.

344
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] We're going to see the first Brazilian covered bond very soon.

345
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:13,000
[SPEAKER_00] And as my final comment, the central and eastern Europe.

346
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] And that is a topic that I'm going to leave to the next speakers, to Jacek and Andrea.

347
00:28:18,000 --> 00:28:19,000
[SPEAKER_00] Thank you.

